  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "BUz47aSStuIiH5yF2ZOGQ8lAgC0=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Claim\n\nSwarm's **Access Control Trie (ACT)** provides selective multi-party access to encrypted content using per-grantee Diffie-Hellman key derivation rather than a single shared decryption key.\n\n## Evidence\n\n- Publisher derives a unique lookup key + access key for each grantee from that grantee's public key (Diffie-Hellman)\n- The ACT is itself a Swarm manifest storing encrypted access keys \u2014 metadata (including the grantee list) is encrypted\n- **Timestamped history**: grantees can access the version they were granted even after revocation\n- API: `POST /grantee` (create list), `PATCH /grantee/{address}` (add/revoke)\n- bee-js: `bee.createGrantees()`, `bee.getGrantees()`, `bee.patchGrantees()`\n\n## Why it matters\n\nThe adapter currently shares via `SHA-256(sender_address:recipient_address)`, which means anyone knowing both addresses can derive the key \u2014 not revocable. ACT is the proper primitive: per-recipient keys, revocation, and encrypted grantee lists. Migrating to ACT is on the roadmap.\n",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:45.000Z"
    }
  },
